title: User query: Plan description from client LLM
log: Find the distribution of customers based on how many orders they have placed. Include customers with zero orders. Ignore any orders whose comment contains the substring ‘special’ followed by ‘requests’. Count how many customers fall into each order-count group and output the number of customers per group. Sort by most orders. Output in textfile.

title: Agent: SpecifierAgent Output
log: Compute the distribution of customers by the total number of orders placed, including customers with zero orders. Exclude any orders whose comments contain the phrase "special requests" (i.e., the substring 'special' followed by 'requests'). After filtering, determine, for each customer, how many orders they placed. Group customers by their order count and report the number of customers in each group. Sort the groups by descending order count (most orders first). Output the results to a text file.

log.thoughts: Selected tables likely contain customer dimension data and their related orders. Customers provides unique customers, Orders links to customers via customer_id and contains the comment field used to filter out orders with 'special requests'. No text files are needed since data is in relational tables.

steps.detailed_description: Load the customers and orders tables as inputs. Use both datasets to establish the base entities (customers) and their potential orders.

Filter the orders to exclude any with comments containing the substring 'special' followed by 'requests' (i.e., exclude orders where comments includes 'special' and 'requests' in sequence). Input: orders table. Output: filtered_orders table.

Left-join customers with filtered_orders on customer_id to produce a dataset of customer-order pairs, ensuring every customer appears at least once with possible null order fields when there are zero orders. Output: customer_orders_joined.

For each customer, compute the number of orders by counting non-null order identifiers from the joined dataset. This yields one row per customer with customer_id and order_count, including customers with zero orders (order_count = 0). Output: per_customer_order_counts.

Group customers by their order_count and count how many customers fall into each group. Sort order_count groups in descending order of the count of customers, effectively producing a distribution like: (order_count, customer_count). Output: distribution_by_order_count.
Write the distribution results to a text file as the final output.

log.thoughts: The plan loads both customers and orders, filters undesired orders, preserves zero-order customers via a left join, counts per-customer orders, builds the distribution by grouping on order_count, and finally writes the result to text. This sequence maintains data lineage and satisfies the requirement to include zero-order customers and exclude certain orders.
